Unfair trade practice means a trading method that, for the purpose of promoting the sale, use or supply of any goods or of any service, employs unfair or deceptive means.  
Section 2(1)(r) of the Indian Consumer Protection Act, 1986 defines it as “a trade practice which, for the purpose of promoting the sale, use or supply of any goods or services, adopts any unfair method or unfair or deceptive practice,” and it includes, inter-alia:  

• making any false or misleading representation about the quality, quantity, grade, composition, style or model of goods or services;  
• falsely claiming sponsorship, approval, performance characteristics, accessories, uses or benefits;  
• offering goods at ‘bargain prices’ when the seller has no intention or adequate stock to sell at that price;  
• offering gifts, prizes or other items with the intent of not providing them as offered;  
• misleading the public concerning the prices at which goods or services have actually been sold;  
• hoarding or destroying goods, or refusing to sell them, with the intent of raising prices.  

Thus, any method of trade that misleads, deceives or otherwise injures consumers in order to increase sales constitutes an unfair trade practice.
